  "maleQty": 1,
  "language": "en"
}




# =============================================================
# REFERENCE GUIDE
# =============================================================
#
# ── THE DEPENDENCY CHAIN ─────────────────────────────────────
#
#   [1] Health check          → confirm server is up
#        ↓
#   [2] Create intent         → (ID not used in steps 4/5 — see two-ID problem) ONLY creates a PaymentIntent, does NOT trigger the webhook
#        ↓
#  Actual flow starts here — the rest of the steps depend on you running the stripe trigger command in your terminal
#   [3] stripe trigger        → TERMINAL COMMAND, not HTTP
#        ↓                      fires webhook → saves order + creates tickets in DB
#        ↓                      prints pi_XXX in Terminal 1 logs  ← copy this
#        ↓
#   [4] GET /qr               → needs: pi_XXX from Terminal 1 logs
#   [5] GET /tickets          → needs: pi_XXX from Terminal 1 logs → gives you: qrToken
#        ↓
#   [6] POST /scanner/auth    → needs: PIN from .env → gives you: bearer token
#        ↓
#   [7] GET /scanner/tickets  → needs: bearer token
#   [8] POST /scanner/scan    → needs: bearer token + qrToken (from step 5)
#   [9] POST /scanner/scan    → same qrToken again → proves duplicate rejection
#  [10] GET /scanner/tickets  → proves count dropped by 1
#
# ── WHERE EACH VALUE COMES FROM ──────────────────────────────
#
#   paymentIntentId  → Terminal 1 server logs after Step 3 (NOT Step 2 response)
#   bearer token     → "token" field in Step 6 response body
#   qrToken          → "tickets[0].qrToken" in Step 5 response body
#
#
# ── THE TWO-ID PROBLEM (most common confusion) ───────────────
#
#   Step 2 creates a PaymentIntent → gives you pi_AAA
#   Step 3 (stripe trigger) creates a DIFFERENT PaymentIntent → pi_BBB
#
#   pi_AAA and pi_BBB are never the same.
#   stripe trigger always creates its own brand new fake payment.
#
#   Steps 4 and 5 need the ID of whichever payment the WEBHOOK processed.
#   That is ALWAYS the ID printed in your Terminal 1 server logs.
#
#   So the rule is simple:
#     After Step 3 → look at Terminal 1 logs → find the line:
#       [Webhook] ✅ payment_intent.succeeded
#       [Webhook]    ID: pi_XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX   ← use this
#
#
# ── WHY 0 TICKETS GET CREATED ────────────────────────────────
#
#   Plain "stripe trigger payment_intent.succeeded" sends empty metadata.
#   Your backend reads femaleQty/maleQty from metadata → gets 0/0 → 0 tickets.
#
#   Always use the --override version:
#     stripe trigger payment_intent.succeeded \
#       --override payment_intent:metadata.femaleQty=2 \
#       --override payment_intent:metadata.maleQty=1
#
# ── COMMON ERRORS ────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   "Missing stripe-signature header"
#   → You tried to POST to /webhooks/stripe from this file.
#     That is impossible — webhooks must come from Stripe CLI or Stripe itself.
#
#   { "status": "pending" } on GET /tickets
#   → Two possible causes:
#     a) Webhook hasn't fired — run stripe trigger in terminal
#     b) You used the Step 2 paymentIntentId instead of the one from logs
#
#   401 Unauthorized on scanner endpoints
#   → Your bearer token is expired, misspelled, or missing "Bearer " prefix
#     Token expires after 12 hours — just run Step 6 again to get a new one
#
#   "Incorrect PIN."
#   → Check SCANNER_PIN value in your .env file (default: 1234)
#
#   count still 3 after scanning in Step 10
#   → The scan in Step 8 may have failed — check the Step 8 response
#     It must say "accepted" for the ticket to be marked used
#
# =============================================================
